}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_I14a61792f0de11ef882ba76dbbf70}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_I14a61792f0de11ef882ba76dbbf70}
\par 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=h&pubNum=176284&cite=0282461101&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RQ&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
SILBERMAN
}}}
\sa200 
\sb200 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
, Judge.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_anchor_I14bb9b61f0de11ef882ba76dbbf70}{\*\bkmkend co_anchor_I14bb9b61f0de11ef882ba76dbbf70}
\par 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Neapolitan Enterprises, LLC, appeals a final order dismissing with prejudice its amended complaint for declaratory and injunctive relief in its action against Olde Naples Building LLC and Broad Avenue LLC (collectively, Olde Naples) and the City of Naples. The Olde Naples Building (the Building) and its parking space credits are at the center of this dispute. In this action Neapolitan was seeking to void the City\rquote s alleged ultra vires act of confirming seventy-six parking credits in a letter from the City\rquote s planning director that served to reduce the Building\rquote s parking space obligation. Neapolitan contends that the City should have followed the variance process which would have required the City to give affected landowners, such as Neapolitan, notice and an opportunity to be heard. We reverse the dismissal of the amended complaint and remand for further proceedings.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The pertinent facts for purposes of this appeal are taken from the allegations in the amended complaint, and those allegations must be taken as true in considering a motion to dismiss. 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2034790759&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_664&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_664" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Hussey v. Collier Cty.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 158 So.3d 661, 664 (Fla. 2d DCA 2014)
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. In November 2010 a notice indicated that the City\rquote s Design Review Board (DRB) would have a hearing on architectural renovations to the fa\u231\'3fade of the Building. The DRB does not have the authority to make zoning or parking decisions and did not make any decision on parking. In March 2011 Olde Naples sought a building permit to perform renovations to stabilize the Building. The permit requested confirmation of parking space credit calculations to \u8220\'3fsecure the parking nonconformity.\u8221\'3f A notation on the submitted plans by Planning Director Robin Singer (the Planning Director) states, \u8220\'3fParking Credits as shown on Page A10 have not been officially determined as of 4/12/11. Parking credits, if any, will be determined by the Planning Director.\u8221\'3f A building permit was issued.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
A letter of September 2, 2011, from the Planning Director to Neapolitan\rquote s counsel notified Neapolitan of the administrative decision to approve parking calculations supplied by Olde Naples and outlining reasons why the City accepted Olde Naples\rquote  parking calculations. The Planning Director\rquote s notation on the submitted plans and her letter of September 2, 2011, are attached as exhibits to the amended complaint. The result of the City\rquote s actions is to allow Olde Naples to use the Building as a restaurant without providing any off-street parking. The seventy-six parking spaces that Olde Naples did not provide represents over one-third of the public parking available in the Third Street Commercial District.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Neapolitan filed two administrative appeals with the City, but the City refused to hear the appeals. On October 3, 2011, Neapolitan filed a petition for writ of certiorari with the circuit court. Neapolitan asserted that the City had employed a flawed procedure to, in effect, grant a variance that deprived Neapolitan of due process and that competent, substantial evidence did not support the City\rquote s decision.
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 On July 20, 2012, the circuit court denied (rather than dismissed) the petition. But the circuit court specifically determined that it did not have jurisdiction to review the petition because the Planning Director made the parking determination in the letter of September 2, 2011. The circuit 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_3926_589_1}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_3926_589_1}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
*589
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 court concluded that the parking decision made in the letter was not quasi-judicial action reviewable by a petition for writ of certiorari. On second-tier review, this court denied Neapolitan\rquote s petition without a written opinion.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Meanwhile, on July 13, 2012, Neapolitan had also filed a complaint for declaratory and injunctive relief in the circuit court. On November 11, 2013, Neapolitan filed its first amended complaint that is the subject of this appeal. Olde Naples and the City filed motions to dismiss that argued, among other things, that Neapolitan failed to file a petition for writ of certiorari to challenge DRB Resolution 10\u8211\'3f22, issued on November 24, 2010, and that Neapolitan\rquote s claims were barred by res judicata and collateral estoppel.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
After a hearing on motions to dismiss, the trial court dismissed the amended complaint with prejudice. In its order granting the motions to dismiss, the trial court found, \u8220\'3fOn November 24, 2010, DRB Resolution 10\u8211\'3f22 was issued, approving [Olde Naples\rquote ] plans to renovate the [Building] and determined that the [Building] qualifies for an allowance of 76 parking space credits.\u8221\'3f The trial court further found that the City granted to Olde Naples \u8220\'3fa parking variance on November 24, 2010, and as such the proper remedy available to [Neapolitan] to determine whether procedural due process was afforded would have been through a timely filed Petition for Writ of Certiorari.\u8221\'3f Determining that Neapolitan failed to timely challenge the 2010 DRB resolution, the trial court concluded that any issues regarding the DRB were procedurally barred. Thus, the trial court granted the motion to dismiss the amended complaint with prejudice and dismissed the action.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F12038189609_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf37 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[1]
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 We employ a de novo review of the dismissal of a complaint with prejudice. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2033336199&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_615&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_615" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Ferguson Enters., Inc. v. Astro Air Conditioning & Heating, Inc.,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 137 So.3d 613, 615 (Fla. 2d DCA 2014)
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. A motion to dismiss does not concern fact issues; rather, it tests the legal sufficiency of the complaint. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2034790759&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_664&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_664" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Hussey,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 158 So.3d at 664
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. In ruling on a motion to dismiss, a trial court is limited to considering the four corners of the complaint along with the attachments incorporated into the complaint. 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Id.; 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2033369085&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_376&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_376" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
May v. Salter,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 139 So.3d 375, 376 (Fla. 1st DCA 2014)
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
. In the trial court and on appeal, the court must accept the allegations in the complaint as true. 
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2034790759&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_664&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_664" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Hussey,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 158 So.3d at 664
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
