{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2029470299&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_984&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_984" }{\fldrslt 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Jasser,
}
}
{\b0 \cf26 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 103 So.3d at 984 n. 2
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 (stating that there were \u8220\'3fsufficient references in the complaint itself to the history of the entire matter so that the issue may be determined\u8221\'3f).
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_hn_anchor_F32038189609_1" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b1 \cf37 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
[3]
}}}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Here, the trial court took judicial notice only of the certiorari order and this court\rquote s per curiam denial of the second-tier certiorari petition. The trial court found that on November 24, 2010, DRB Resolution 10\u8211\'3f22 was issued, that the DRB determined that the Building qualified for an allowance of seventy-six parking space credits, and that the City granted to Olde Naples a parking variance on November 24, 2010. The allegations of the amended complaint, its attachments, and the certiorari order do not support the above findings that the trial court made in granting the motion to dismiss.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The amended complaint alleged that in November 2010 a representative of Neapolitan received notice of a DRB hearing concerning proposed changes to the Building\rquote s fa\u231\'3fade; that the DRB does not have the power to make zoning or parking decisions pursuant to the City\rquote s Land Development Code; and that \u8220\'3f[t]he DRB did not make any decision on the issue of parking.\u8221\'3f The amended complaint also alleged, and attached as Exhibit 1, the following notation the Planning Director made on April 12, 2011, on the submitted plans: \u8220\'3fParking Credits as shown on Page A10 have not been officially determined as of 4/12/11. Parking credits, if any, will be determined by the Planning Director.\u8221\'3f
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Based on the documents the trial court considered, nothing shows that the DRB decided the issue of parking credits in November 2010. Thus, the trial court\rquote s legal conclusion is incorrect that Neapolitan \u8220\'3ffailed to timely challenge the City Planning Department\rquote s administrative determination contained in DRB Resolution 10\u8211\'3f22\u8221\'3f and that any challenge to issues with respect to the DRB is procedurally barred.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Even if we considered the DRB resolution, it does not establish that the DRB determined parking credits. The resolution states in pertinent part \u8220\'3f[t]hat petition 10\u8211\'3fDRB22 is hereby approved for Final Design Review approval for a substantial change to the fa\u231\'3fade including landscaping and lighting for the Naples Company Building aka Olde Naples Building\u8221\'3f in conformance with the architect\rquote s plans. Nothing in the resolution mentions parking. The minutes to the hearing reflect that Barbara Walker on behalf of Neapolitan requested that the DRB limit approval to a preliminary one because Olde Naples was claiming grandfathering rights to seventy-six spaces that did not exist.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Olde Naples argues on appeal that because the resolution granted the application for final design approval without imposing any limitation regarding the parking issue that the DRB determined parking credits. But the later notation by the Planning Director in April 2011 confirmed that parking credits had yet to be determined.
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Thus, even if we considered the resolution and minutes, at best there is an issue of fact that cannot be resolved on a motion to dismiss. 
}
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \i1 \fs20 
{\b0 \cf24 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i1 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
See 
}
}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://www.westlaw.com/Link/Document/FullText?findType=Y&serNum=2034790759&pubNum=0003926&originatingDoc=I28b869c3c85411e5a795ac035416da91&refType=RP&fi=co_pp_sp_3926_664&originationContext=document&vr=3.0&rs=cblt1.0&transitionType=DocumentItem&contextData=(sc.CustomDigest)#co_pp_sp_3926_664" }{\fldrslt 
